REPHRASE Case Study: UPI / Online Payment Fraud

UPI fraud is one of the most common cybercrimes in India today, especially with the rise of apps like Google Pay and PhonePe. It involves tricking people into authorizing payments or revealing sensitive details such as OTPs or UPI PINs.

A typical case involves a scammer contacting the victim through a phone call or WhatsApp message, often pretending to be a bank representative, delivery agent, or even a buyer from platforms like OLX. For example, a college student trying to sell a used phone online receives a message from a “buyer” who agrees instantly and sends a payment request. The scammer then guides the student to “accept” a collect request, claiming it will transfer money. In reality, the student ends up approving a payment instead. In some cases, the fraudster may also ask the victim to install a screen-sharing app, allowing them to see OTPs and access banking apps directly.

These scams usually target students, elderly individuals, and people who are not fully aware of how UPI transactions work. The consequences can be serious, including immediate financial loss, stress, and even misuse of personal data.

This situation could have been avoided if, the student had known that receiving money never require entering a UPI PIN or approving a request. Being cautious, verifying the source, and avoiding unknown payment requests are key to staying safe.
